liveBlogPostPrepared.plaintext: Record bookings and transaction values have seen online travel agency Webjet return to profit. Webjet's swung from a net loss of nearly $82 million for the 2022 financial year to a net profit of $14.5 million for 2023. Revenue jumped by 164 per cent to $364 million over the year. The company's WebBeds online marketplace for the travel trade helped Webjet's business return to pre-pandemic levels over the second half of the year. But investors get no dividend payout. Webjet's managing director John Guscic was upbeat. "Webjet has emerged from the pandemic better placed to deliver growth than ever before." "Even though travel has yet to full return to where it was, in the second half of 2023 we saw group bookings, total transaction value, revenue and ebitda all ahead of where they were when the pandemic hit."
liveBlogPostPrepared.title: Record bookings drive Webjet turnaround

children.content: Record bookings and transaction values have seen online travel agency Webjet return to profit.
Webjet's swung from a net loss of nearly $82 million for the 2022 financial year to a net profit of $14.5 million for 2023.
Revenue jumped by 164 per cent to $364 million over the year.
The company's WebBeds online marketplace for the travel trade helped Webjet's business return to pre-pandemic levels over the second half of the year.
But investors get no dividend payout.
Webjet's managing director John Guscic was upbeat.
"Webjet has emerged from the pandemic better placed to deliver growth than ever before."

liveBlogPostPrepared.plaintext: Russian gas pipeline operator Gazprom says its net profit fell more than 40 per cent to 1.226 trillion roubles ($23.84 billion) last year because of a tax increase in the second half. The company said it would not pay a full year dividend to investors, after it paid a half year dividend of 1.2 trillion roubles ($22.68 billion). Western countries imposed a raft of sanctions over Russia's invasion of Ukraine, but Gazprom's gas exports have not been directly affected. However, export volumes almost halved last year to 101 billion cubic metres. Gazprom shares fell 3.4 per cent.
liveBlogPostPrepared.title: Gazprom profit falls 40 per cent

children.content: Russian gas pipeline operator Gazprom says its net profit fell more than 40 per cent to 1.226 trillion roubles ($23.84 billion) last year because of a tax increase in the second half.
The company said it would not pay a full year dividend to investors, after it paid a half year dividend of 1.2 trillion roubles ($22.68 billion).
Western countries imposed a raft of sanctions over Russia's invasion of Ukraine, but Gazprom's gas exports have not been directly affected.
However, export volumes almost halved last year to 101 billion cubic metres.
Gazprom shares fell 3.4 per cent.

liveBlogPostPrepared.plaintext: Representatives of US president Joe Biden and congressional Republicans ended another round of debt talks with no signs of progress on raising the US government's borrowing limit. US Treasury Secretary Janet Yellen has warned the US government may not have enough money to pay all its bills as soon as June 1. That could cause a default that would hit the US economy and push borrowing costs higher. White House negotiators met with their Republican counterparts for about two hours. White House spokesperson Karine Jean-Pierre called the talks "incredibly tough." "Both sides have to understand that they're not going to get everything they want." Here's more from senior business correspondent Peter Ryan.
liveBlogPostPrepared.title: No signs of progress in US debt ceiling talks
